%I A394177 #12 Mar 13 2026 11:38:22
%S A394177 3,9,15,21,27,33,35,39,45,51,55,57,63,69,75,77,81,87,93,95,99,105,111,
%T A394177 115,117,119,123,129,135,141,143,147,153,155,159,161,165,171,177,183,
%U A394177 187,189,195,201,203,207,209,213,215,219,225,235,237,243,245,249,253,255,261,267
%N A394177 Odd k such that there are exactly 2 bases 1 <= b <= k-1 in which k is a strong pseudoprime.
%C A394177 In other words, odd k>1 such that there are no bases 2 <= b <= k-2 in which k is a strong pseudoprime.
%C A394177 Odd k = 2*m+1 such that A071294(m) = 2.
%C A394177 According to the formula of A071294, k is a term if and only if k has a prime factor congruent to 3 modulo 4 and gcd(p-1,k-1) is a power of 2 for every prime factor p of k.
%H A394177 Jianing Song, <a href="/A394177/b394177.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A394177 105 = 3*5*7 is a term since gcd(3-1,105-1) = 2, gcd(5-1,105-1) = 4, and gcd(7-1,105-1) = 2 are all powers of 2.
%e A394177 231 = 3*7*11 is not a term since gcd(11-1,231-1) = 10. Indeed, A071294((231-1)/2) = 10.
%e A394177 221 = 13*17 is not a term: even if gcd(13-1,221-1) = 4 and gcd(17-1,221-1) = 4, it does not have a prime factor congruent to 3 modulo 4. Indeed, A071294((221-1)/2) = 6.
%o A394177 (PARI) isA394177(k) = if(k%2==0, return(0)); my(f=factor(k), r=#f~, found_3_mod_4=0); for(i=1, r, if(!isprimepower(2*gcd(f[i,1]-1,k-1)), return(0)); if(f[i,1]%4==3, found_3_mod_4=1)); return(found_3_mod_4)
%Y A394177 Cf. A071294 (number of bases), A329759 (numbers with the most bases possible).
%Y A394177 A394182, which is the sequence where "strong pseudoprime" is replaced by "Euler-Jacobi pseudoprime", is a supersequence.
%K A394177 nonn,easy,new
%O A394177 1,1
%A A394177 _Jianing Song_, Mar 11 2026
